The issue with the current implementation is that it is only searching for the presence of the keywords "TABLE" and "COLUMNS" in the text. However, it is not considering the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns.

To address this issue, we can modify the function to analyze the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns. We can look for patterns such as rows of data with consistent column separators or headers for each column to identify a table or columns.

Let's update the function to implement this improved logic:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const headerRow = lines[1].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the second line by multiple spaces
    const dataRow = lines[2].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the third line by multiple spaces
    if (headerRow.length === dataRow.length) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

By analyzing the structure of the text data, we can determine whether it represents a table, columns, both, or neither based on the presence of consistent column separators and headers.

The text you provided does not seem to conform to a typical table or columns structure, which is why the function is incorrectly identifying it as a "TABLE" instead of "COLUMNS". 
To address this issue, we can update the function to look for consistent column separators and data under each header. We'll also ignore any headers that contain multiple words and try to identify column structures solely based on data alignment.

Here's the updated function to address these changes:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const firstLine = lines[0].trim();
  const secondLine = lines[1] ? lines[1].trim() : ""; // Handle case where there is only 1 line
  const thirdLine = lines[2] ? lines[2].trim() : "";  // Handle case where there are only 1 or 2 lines

  if (firstLine.includes("  ") && secondLine.includes("  ") && !thirdLine.includes("  ")) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const headerRow = lines[1].replace(/\s{2,}/g, ' ').split(' ');
    const dataRow = lines[2].replace(/\s{2,}/g, ' ').split(' ');
    if (headerRow.length === dataRow.length && headerRow.every((item, index) => item.length === dataRow[index].length)) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  return "NORMAL";
}
```

This updated function will now look for consistent column separators in the first and second lines to identify columns, and it will check for consistent column structures in the second and third lines to identify a table. If the text does not match either of those structures, it will return "NORMAL".
